<dl id="n53111j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53111j">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53111j"> 111(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ 1st / k at Clontarf, <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53111j"><li>FW 99.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n53111j">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n53111j">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53111j">MS BL 47476a-202</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:425 <a name="dd10" href="../../FF/fdra/dda.htm#dd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd10.htm#n53111j">Draft: I.4&sect;1.10</a>/2.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The name O&apos;Reilly (Irish <i>O Ragh(e)allaigh</i>, <i>O Radheollaigh</i> and variants) derives from Ragh(e)allach + /O/ (<i>&oacute;</i> or <i>ua</i>, from <i>&oacute;gh&aacute;</i>: grandchild), with various opinions as to the derivation of Ragh(e)allach. Some say it derives from the Irish <i>ragh</i> (a race or tribe) + <i>ealtach</i> (gregarious) &mdash; Joyce&apos;s &lsquo;eallach (a burden)&rsquo; is an error copied via the newspaper article from John O&apos;Hart&apos;s <i>Irish Pedigrees</i> (Dublin, 1881). Others see in it the Irish <i>r&aacute;dh</i> (a saying) + <i>&eacute;olach</i> (skilful, learned). Yet others say it comes from the Irish <i>r&oacute;ghalach</i> (valiant, warlike). The family itself can ultimately be traced back to Maolm&oacute;ardha (Latinized Milesius and Anglicized Myles or Miles) &mdash; itself derived from Irish <i>maol</i>, a hillock, also bald, blunt, obtuse, and humble, + <i>m&oacute;rdha</i> (proud, magnanimous). Maolm&oacute;rdha was a descendant of Roarc, descendant of Heremon, one of the two progenitors of Ireland, and ascendant of Ragheallach, who <mark>perished at the Battle of Clontarf</mark> in 1014 and from whom the family derives its name.]</font> <small> &ldquo;Irish Family Names: O'Reilly&rdquo;, <a name="WIT21jan33" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WIT21jan33"><cite title="source">Weekly Irish Times</cite></a> (21 January 1933) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
